1
00:00:01,988 --> 00:00:31,184
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:33,156 --> 00:00:39,207
So I thought this evening we'd tackle this crucial role of desire and intention.

3
00:00:39,988 --> 00:00:42,753
So there are three words that we have to be clear about.

4
00:00:44,396 --> 00:00:47,402
Tanha, chanda and chetana.

5
00:00:48,884 --> 00:00:52,651
So now this word tanha originally means a drought.

6
00:00:53,031 --> 00:00:59,362
So from that you get the idea of thirst and it's used only for unwholesome desires.

7
00:01:00,304 --> 00:01:04,533
And it always is included in dependent origination, right?

8
00:01:04,552 --> 00:01:12,326
In the five middle factors, which are the ones that are a process.

9
00:01:12,525 --> 00:01:16,028
So first of all, you have a contact with one of your sense bases.

10
00:01:16,469 --> 00:01:18,632
Remember the mind, heart is a sense base.

11
00:01:19,171 --> 00:01:26,498
Something has to come up into that base of consciousness, moods, emotions, thoughts, images.

12
00:01:27,819 --> 00:01:32,763
And then there's a relationship to what we are experiencing.

13
00:01:32,924 --> 00:01:41,352
So we give it first of all, excuse me, we give it first of all, a name, a concept, and then we have a feeling arises with it.

14
00:01:41,433 --> 00:02:08,740
and dependent on those we have that reaction that we call a desire that desire remember is coming from a conditioning of wanting and not wanting right and in this case it's always unwholesome independence origination because it describes how we create suffering for ourselves and then after that you have an identity i i want and then there's the empowerment

15
00:02:08,804 --> 00:02:15,759
And that's where we make a distinction between the desire and an intention.

16
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:16,521
OK.

17
00:02:18,847 --> 00:02:21,873
So if I take an example, you see an apple.

18
00:02:22,114 --> 00:02:24,901
So the first is just a seeing an object.

19
00:02:25,301 --> 00:02:26,002
Right.

20
00:02:26,022 --> 00:02:27,706
It's round, etc.

21
00:02:27,872 --> 00:02:44,969
and then it's given a name apple and with the word apple that comes a nice feeling usually and then you might feel hungry so there's a desire for the apple which may come from just ordinary appetite but in this case with tanha it becomes because we're greedy

22
00:02:45,187 --> 00:02:47,049
And then you identify with that.

23
00:02:47,549 --> 00:02:49,211
I want that apple.

24
00:02:50,151 --> 00:02:54,856
And you can see there how the language confuses us.

25
00:02:54,937 --> 00:02:58,800
It creates a delusion, gives you the idea that the I comes first.

26
00:02:59,360 --> 00:03:04,105
I want the apple, but actually it comes towards the end of that process.

27
00:03:04,925 --> 00:03:09,151
Once you have that identity, then you empower that desire.

28
00:03:09,651 --> 00:03:13,354
And that's when you become, you become an apple eater.

29
00:03:13,375 --> 00:03:13,675
Okay.

30
00:03:16,252 --> 00:03:18,074
So that's the first word, tanha.

31
00:03:18,575 --> 00:03:19,796
The second word is chanda.

32
00:03:19,937 --> 00:03:26,044
Now, actually, in the discourses, chanda can either be wholesome or unwholesome.

33
00:03:26,545 --> 00:03:37,519
But in later Buddhism, the sort of more Abhidhamma commentarial side, the chanda tended to be used only for what was a wholesome desire.

34
00:03:37,538 --> 00:03:45,889
So we do need desire, but we need those desires that lead to liberation, that lead to happiness in this very life.

35
00:03:47,302 --> 00:03:48,765
So that's chanda.

36
00:03:49,287 --> 00:03:54,956
And we can translate it as a sort of desire.

37
00:03:55,899 --> 00:03:59,525
And you've got to be careful.

38
00:03:59,786 --> 00:04:02,129
These words are so confusing.

39
00:04:02,570 --> 00:04:07,539
A resolution is the energy of wanting something.

40
00:04:10,169 --> 00:04:12,671
Now I'll tell you where the confusion comes in a minute.

41
00:04:13,633 --> 00:04:15,615
The third word is chaitana.

42
00:04:15,775 --> 00:04:20,360
Now chaitana is connected to the word citta, which means mind.

43
00:04:21,081 --> 00:04:24,564
So here we're talking about intention or purpose.

44
00:04:25,685 --> 00:04:27,908
So there are these two things.

45
00:04:27,928 --> 00:04:32,733
There's a desire, which can be wholesome and unwholesome, and there's the purpose.

46
00:04:33,591 --> 00:04:41,514
Now the importance of that is that the desire itself, the actual energy, the wanting, is neutral.

47
00:04:42,076 --> 00:04:47,752
What makes it wholesome and unwholesome is the chaitanya, your purpose for doing something.

48
00:04:52,271 --> 00:05:04,002
uh now to get a feel for what that desire is as opposed to purpose you might say one thing you can do is if you're very hungry

49
00:05:04,067 --> 00:05:26,716
just sit with the food in front of you and just feel the desire right so the the purpose is obvious you want to eat the food but by sitting there just looking at the food and smelling that the the aromas and all that and you you can get that feel for what desire is as an energy yeah

50
00:05:27,473 --> 00:05:34,461
If you want to really experience it, this is what I used to say, but it's been ruined now.

51
00:05:35,002 --> 00:05:39,009
I used to say, turn on the TV when it's your favorite program.

52
00:05:39,548 --> 00:05:43,595
Sorry, sit in front of the TV when it's your favorite program and don't turn it on.

53
00:05:44,276 --> 00:05:47,379
But unfortunately, I, a player, has ruined all that.

54
00:05:49,502 --> 00:05:51,485
You know, you can always catch up with a bit of a pain.

55
00:05:52,045 --> 00:05:52,586
Never mind.

56
00:05:55,468 --> 00:06:09,367
So if we take an example from, say, physics of throwing a stone, the energy within the arm is transferred into the stone and you cannot separate the force from the stone.

57
00:06:10,228 --> 00:06:14,312
You can't stop it in mid-air and say, well, look, this is the force and this is the stone.

58
00:06:14,853 --> 00:06:16,254
They're all one.

59
00:06:16,636 --> 00:06:19,839
But the purpose of throwing the stone can be various.

60
00:06:19,819 --> 00:06:27,218
When I'm walking around the property here, some of the stones from the car park have come onto the path where they shouldn't be.

61
00:06:27,237 --> 00:06:30,685
So I might just pick one up and flick it back onto the car park.

62
00:06:30,786 --> 00:06:31,567
Yeah.

63
00:06:31,750 --> 00:06:37,959
I might find a flat stone, we have a little pond, and I might throw it on the pond to see it skim just for the joy of it.

64
00:06:39,362 --> 00:06:40,745
But then we also have rabbits.

65
00:06:40,925 --> 00:06:53,786
Now, most of you or some of you will remember my experience with moles and how we had to get rid of the lawns and create a garden.

66
00:06:54,466 --> 00:06:58,213
So now we have rabbits who come in and dig little holes.

67
00:06:58,192 --> 00:07:25,769
so i might be tempted to pick up a stone not to harm the rabbit you understand but to give it the impression that it shouldn't actually be digging a hole in the garden and they've got a whole meadow to go and do it in so these are what you might say you're in my intentions but the actual energy or the desire to throw the stone is neutral right there's a there's a distinction there

68
00:07:27,892 --> 00:07:29,576
And the Buddha makes it quite clear.

69
00:07:29,716 --> 00:07:37,827
He says, I say to you that it is the chaitanya that creates a kamma.

70
00:07:38,348 --> 00:07:44,738
Now, kamma here is not the same as karma, which has come into our language as comeuppance and what you deserve.

71
00:07:45,300 --> 00:07:47,302
Kamma here just means an action.

72
00:07:47,704 --> 00:07:51,569
Now, remember that when you repeat an action, you create a habit.

73
00:07:52,470 --> 00:07:58,416
And as we know, a collection of habits is your personality, your character.

74
00:07:58,797 --> 00:08:01,819
And once you've got that, then your destiny is assured.

75
00:08:02,380 --> 00:08:08,307
So something is driving us to our destiny and it's these habits that we've collected throughout life.

76
00:08:09,048 --> 00:08:17,036
And our purpose, of course, is to discern those habits that lead us to perdition and those habits that lead to liberation.

77
00:08:19,226 --> 00:08:23,233
I'll give you another example, actually, which comes from the Vinaya, the rule of the monks.

78
00:08:24,334 --> 00:08:43,462
If, for instance, I see somebody's mobile and I'm very attracted to it, and I think to myself, I'd like that mobile, because they've left it unguarded on a piece of furniture or something.

79
00:08:44,184 --> 00:08:52,342
Now, if I just allow the thoughts to process, in a sense, I'm building up a wrong intention.

80
00:08:52,923 --> 00:09:03,628
Now, it might be that this intention becomes so strong that I actually move towards the mobile with the intention at the back of my mind to slip it in my pocket.

81
00:09:03,878 --> 00:09:16,960
now and then i stop myself see i stop myself in that process what the heck's going on you see so this is called a dukkata this is already a uh a small offense right it's not serious

82
00:09:17,631 --> 00:09:30,009
However, the desire for this mobile overtakes me and I again approach the mobile and I just put my hand on it and then, in a sort of horror, I take it back.

83
00:09:31,072 --> 00:09:34,395
Now, this is what's called a Gardevoir, it's a serious offence.

84
00:09:34,937 --> 00:09:40,365
I've actually gone and touched the object that I'm wanting.

85
00:09:41,711 --> 00:10:10,284
but again the desire for this mobile completely overtakes me i go to it i i touch it and i move it a nano centimeter that's all just a nano centimeter i suddenly realize what i've done i drop it and i walk away it's too late as far as the veneer is concerned i've committed an act of stealing even if i don't get it it's an act of stealing and in the veneer this is a very serious offense uh it's called a paragica

86
00:10:10,264 --> 00:10:19,177
So Parājika translates as end of life, which means that you have to leave the order and you can't join it again in this lifetime.

87
00:10:19,818 --> 00:10:34,480
So this is an example to show the process of how we can unwittingly be developing a desire which then suddenly grabs us and we do something that we ought not to have done.

88
00:10:37,384 --> 00:10:39,967
So the model there is don't become a monastic.

89
00:10:42,394 --> 00:10:45,438
So one of two things here now, just as a sort of reflection.

90
00:10:47,240 --> 00:10:52,307
When we have a negative desire, so this is to do with a sense of self.

91
00:10:52,948 --> 00:10:59,498
When we have a negative desire, when we're doing something or saying something, there's always a separation.

92
00:10:59,918 --> 00:11:07,288
You create a duality between the person who doesn't want to do something and what you're actually doing.

93
00:11:07,268 --> 00:11:10,854
So a simple example might be, you know, washing pots.

94
00:11:10,874 --> 00:11:20,168
You're fed up with washing pots, especially if you've got a family and all these pots and pans everywhere and you're fed up with it and you're washing the pots.

95
00:11:20,208 --> 00:11:25,658
Now yourself, the sense of self is I don't, I shouldn't be doing this.

96
00:11:26,399 --> 00:11:29,985
You know, somebody else should be doing this and I'm fed up with doing this.

97
00:11:29,965 --> 00:11:54,994
and you're washing the pots at the same time right so there's a split there between the sense of self and what you're actually doing and that's why sometimes you lose your attention and you drop a pot and break it and then then you're really mad see now um if you have a positive uh craving if you have something that you really want an indulging thing

98
00:11:55,918 --> 00:12:20,626
then here you would immerse you can immerse completely into that experience so it might be that you know you're you're very fond of um horror movies or something like that and and and you're knowing yourself that perhaps you shouldn't be watching these i'm not saying you shouldn't you're saying it to yourself and then you you absorb into the film you lose yourself into the film

99
00:12:21,889 --> 00:12:29,046
Now the problem with going into something from a position of indulgence is that you go in with prejudice.

100
00:12:29,649 --> 00:12:30,533
For instance,

101
00:12:32,065 --> 00:12:33,307
And it's selective.

102
00:12:34,288 --> 00:12:40,975
So for instance, supposing now you go to a restaurant and there's a pizza, right?

103
00:12:41,616 --> 00:12:43,379
So you've had all these pizzas.

104
00:12:43,399 --> 00:12:47,063
So you've got this idea of what a proper pizza ought to be.

105
00:12:47,104 --> 00:12:55,293
And you walk into the restaurant, you ask for a pizza and it just doesn't live up to what you expect a pizza to be.

106
00:12:55,674 --> 00:12:59,759
So you're very disappointed and you eat it, of course, grumbling.

107
00:12:59,740 --> 00:13:04,705
and you won't go back, of course.

108
00:13:04,725 --> 00:13:09,049
But if this was the first pizza you'd ever eaten, you'd be delighted by it.

109
00:13:11,312 --> 00:13:17,658
Another thing is when you are eating something like sticky toffee pudding.

110
00:13:18,080 --> 00:13:25,106
If you eat sticky toffee pudding and what you really want is the sweetness of it,

111
00:13:25,205 --> 00:13:51,515
right so you're you're you're prejudiced towards uh you're biased towards tasting the sweetness of the sticky toffee pudding now it might have all sorts of different subtle flavors but you're unaware of those you've brushed them out as it were because all you're interested in is sweetness and that's what uh indulgence does it just it just looks for what

112
00:13:51,682 --> 00:13:52,886
will gratify it.

113
00:13:53,871 --> 00:14:00,763
So for instance, another distinction would be, say, wine tasters or tea tasters better.

114
00:14:01,705 --> 00:14:30,868
they have to they have to put the tea or the wine on the tongue and roll it round and really be aware of all the tastes that come out from that whereas when we drink tea normally we just have this one taste in mind and if there isn't enough milk we don't like it there's not enough sugar if it's not strong enough and so on and so forth so it's a case of recognizing that whenever we're doing something from a position of indulgence

115
00:14:30,847 --> 00:14:34,951
It's always going to crimp our experience.

116
00:14:35,052 --> 00:14:35,392
That's all.

117
00:14:35,412 --> 00:14:36,393
It's going to limit it.

118
00:14:37,653 --> 00:14:44,500
Apart from, of course, creating a further, greater dependency on it.

119
00:14:44,740 --> 00:14:49,264
They become addictions at various levels or other.

120
00:14:49,504 --> 00:14:53,668
Because you're always trying to satisfy this indulgence.

121
00:14:54,570 --> 00:14:57,732
And the fact of the matter is, it can't be satisfied.

122
00:14:58,674 --> 00:15:01,078
Because that's not where the suffering is coming from.

123
00:15:01,700 --> 00:15:07,489
The suffering is coming from some sense of lack within us, some sense of neediness within us.

124
00:15:08,090 --> 00:15:14,561
And the object that we're using to fulfill it can never cure that sense of neediness.

125
00:15:15,182 --> 00:15:18,466
It just gratifies it for a little while.

126
00:15:19,008 --> 00:15:24,496
The only way we can cure the neediness is by staying with it until it evaporates.

127
00:15:24,679 --> 00:15:29,048
and the energy of that habit is slowly undermined and disappears.

128
00:15:29,830 --> 00:15:38,547
So looking to indulge ourselves, hoping to get rid of the sense, hoping to get rid of that craving is a non-starter.

129
00:15:38,768 --> 00:15:39,789
It just gets worse.

130
00:15:44,840 --> 00:15:46,923
Okay, so...

131
00:15:49,434 --> 00:15:54,346
Now, going back to chaitanya, remember that that's your conditioning factor.

132
00:15:54,427 --> 00:16:00,981
The purpose for which we are doing something is actually reinforcing a habit that we already have.

133
00:16:01,763 --> 00:16:05,030
So it's really important to catch that purpose.

134
00:16:05,010 --> 00:16:16,570
Now, sometimes in the discourses, remember that the word chanda, desire, will be used in a sense of wholesome and unwholesome.

135
00:16:17,211 --> 00:16:26,547
But don't be confused by that if you come across it, because it's always the purpose for which we're doing something which is conditioning us.

136
00:16:27,707 --> 00:16:38,169
Just one little example, which comes from the Visuddhimagga, the path of purification, which was written by a monk called Buddhaghosa in the fifth century.

137
00:16:38,791 --> 00:16:41,817
And it's got to be one of the great spiritual manuals of the world.

138
00:16:41,937 --> 00:16:47,269
I mean, in that book, which is a big tome, and it's as dry as you could imagine.

139
00:16:47,249 --> 00:17:01,490
It has a whole section on the Dharma, a whole section on how to develop beautiful mental states, such as the use of love and metta and things like that, and a whole section on how to develop insight.

140
00:17:01,971 --> 00:17:03,474
So it's a really beautiful book.

141
00:17:03,494 --> 00:17:08,662
And in it, he gives this example of a teacher who's with his students.

142
00:17:09,282 --> 00:17:15,432
And while he's talking, his hand lifts up and he stops and very slowly puts his hand down.

143
00:17:15,903 --> 00:17:17,924
And all the students want to know what happened there.

144
00:17:17,944 --> 00:17:19,967
He said, what happened?

145
00:17:20,426 --> 00:17:22,548
And he said, I didn't note my intention.

146
00:17:23,410 --> 00:17:34,038
In other words, his mindfulness is so acute, is so in the present moment that even the smallest intention would normally be acknowledged.

147
00:17:34,740 --> 00:17:36,300
And in this case, he hadn't.

148
00:17:36,761 --> 00:17:38,824
But he recognized that his hand shouldn't be there.

149
00:17:39,203 --> 00:17:40,565
And he very slowly put it back.

150
00:17:41,086 --> 00:17:43,867
He intended to put his hand back where it ought to be.

151
00:17:44,708 --> 00:17:48,914
So that's how awake we can become in daily life.

152
00:17:49,696 --> 00:17:55,988
And it's especially important to be awake whenever we're making decisions that are of an ethical nature.

153
00:18:00,015 --> 00:18:04,843
So finally, this Chanda, just going back to Chanda,

154
00:18:06,612 --> 00:18:33,327
um is is a desire which grows with the habit of doing something until it becomes a sort of zeal and it becomes part of the four bases of power or success and i've covered that in an earlier moon presentation and that's your zeal and with it there comes the energy to support that aspiration

155
00:18:33,780 --> 00:18:38,346
And then there's the commitment, the devotion of the heart to what you're doing.

156
00:18:38,826 --> 00:18:52,221
And finally, in terms of anything that needs an investigation, the path of insight, there comes that discrimination, that investigation of what we're experiencing.

157
00:18:53,662 --> 00:18:58,928
So this chanda moves from being the slightest

158
00:18:59,126 --> 00:19:26,755
the slightest little desire good desire in this case to a real zeal a real a real desire to achieve something and that's your that's your chanda okay so um just to sum up very quickly we got these three words this tanha which is any desire which we can perceive or realize is unwholesome chanda which is a desire which is wholesome and

159
00:19:26,734 --> 00:19:32,603
What we have to be careful of is this chaitana, the purpose for which we're doing something.

160
00:19:33,044 --> 00:19:35,968
And that sometimes takes a little reflection, right?

161
00:19:35,988 --> 00:19:39,192
Because it can get a bit, how can we say, it can get a bit dodgy.

162
00:19:40,134 --> 00:19:43,759
On the surface of things, we might be doing something for good purpose.

163
00:19:43,779 --> 00:19:47,986
So I'm helping somebody just out of the goodness of my heart, right?

164
00:19:48,526 --> 00:19:50,970
But when they don't thank me, I'm very upset.

165
00:19:50,950 --> 00:20:13,971
so that shows that underneath there you know i'm expecting some sort of praise so trying to get all that stuff into consciousness you know really demands a very uh an ability to to just stop every so often and recognize what's going on inside us very good so uh

166
00:20:15,013 --> 00:20:26,526
I hope my words have not caused any confusion and that by your careful observation of desire, you will drive yourself relentlessly to your liberation from all suffering.

